"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754074","Department for Education","false","2017-09-05","<p>My Rt hon. Friend, the Secretary of State, considered the impact on school places in Oldham as part of the decision making process for the closure of the Collective Spirit Free School.</p><p>For future years, Oldham has been allocated £44.2 million by the department for Education for the new school places the local authority reported were needed from 2017 to 2020. Any change in available capacity will be accounted for in future funding allocations.</p><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-09-05T10:58:35.98Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754074/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754074/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754074/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-07-19","Schools: Oldham","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what assessment she has made of the adequacy of school places in Oldham following the closure of Collective Spirit Free School.","false","Biography information for Jim McMahon","Oldham West and Royton","Jim McMahon","6130"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754075","Department of Health","false","2017-09-05","<p>The information requested is not yet available. The deadline for postgraduate social work students starting courses in September 2017 applying for a bursary is 1 November 2017. A separate deadline of 14 February 2018 applies for postgraduate students starting their course in January 2018.</p><p> </p><p>Undergraduate social work students starting in the 2017 academic year will not be eligible for a bursary until their second year of study.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2017-09-05T13:09:01.887Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754075/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754075/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754075/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-07-19","Social Work: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many applications have been made for social work bursaries for students commencing courses in September 2017; and how many and what proportion of those applications have been successful.","false","Biography information for Mrs Emma Lewell-Buck","South Shields","Mrs Emma Lewell-Buck","6050"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754077","Department for Education","false","2017-09-05","<p>The £4.4 billion Priority School Building Programme is rebuilding or refurbishing those school buildings in the very worst condition across the country. There are two phases of the programme covering a total of 537 schools.</p><p> </p><p>Under the second phase of the programme, individual blocks of accommodation at 277 schools will have their condition need met. This includes Cromer Road School and the Pavilion Study Centre.</p><p> </p><p>The Pavilion Study Centre is currently in the final stages of a feasibility study to consider the options available and determine which one will achieve best value for money. Work will commence on-site once the feasibility is completed and a contractor has been assigned. This is expected to occur between March and May 2018.</p><p> </p><p>Cromer Road School has recently appointed a contractor and design development is now underway. Works will commence on site once planning permission has been received. This is expected to occur between January and March 2018.</p><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-09-05T11:01:41.887Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754077/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754077/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754077/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-07-19","Schools: Chipping Barnet","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, when she expects the rebuilding of Cromer Road School and the Pavilion School, Chipping Barnet to commence.","false","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","Chipping Barnet","Theresa Villiers","6017"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754078","Department for Education","false","2017-09-11","<p>Church and faith schools play an important role in promoting integration and an understanding of different faiths and communities. We will continue to work closely with Church and faith schools to promote and support integration and will set out further details in due course. The Department will provide further information on the <em>Schools that work for everyone </em>consultation, including in relation to the 50% cap on faith-based admissions, in due course.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-09-11T15:33:44.5Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754078/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754078/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754078/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-07-19","Free Schools: Admissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, whether a decision has been made on the proposal to remove the 50 per cent cap on religious selection at free schools; and when her Department plans to publish its response to the Schools that Work for Everyone consultation.","false","Biography information for Kelvin Hopkins","Luton North","Kelvin Hopkins","6260"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754079","Department for Education","false","2017-09-05","<p>My Rt hon. Friend, the Secretary of State, has met with members from across the House to discuss the national funding formula and funding for schools. This includes a meeting on 1 Feburary 2017 with MPs from London, and a DCLG Councillors meeting on 15 March 2017, which was attended by local councillors from across the country, including London.</p><p>In addition, as Minister for School Standards, I have had meetings with a number of members who represent London constituencies, and local councillors from London Councils. I also took part in a Westminster Hall Debate on School Funding in London in March, with contributions from members from a number of constituencies in London.</p><p>Through the national funding formula consultation, we have listened to views from all parts of the country. My Rt hon. Friend, the Secretary of State, announced a total increase of £1.3 billion new money over the next two years. As a result of this additional investment , the formula will provide at least a 0.5% per pupil cash increase for every school in 2018-19, and 1% by 2019-20, comparied to its baseline. We will say more about our formula when we publish the full details later in September.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-09-05T11:31:50.917Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754079/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754079/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754079/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-07-19","Schools: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the Answer of 27 June 2017 to Question 873, what discussions she has had with (a) hon. Members representing for London constituencies, (b) councillors from London local authorities and (c) Greater London Assembly members on school funding since 1 January 2017.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","6327"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754080","Department for Education","false","2017-09-05","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer I gave on 21 July 2017 to question UIN 4640.</p><p><a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2017-07-12/4640/" target="_blank">http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2017-07-12/4640/</a>.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-09-05T11:18:05.413Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754080/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754080/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754080/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-07-19","Department for Education: Written Questions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, when she plans to respond to Question 4640, tabled by the hon. Member for High Peak on 12 July 2017 on children: day care.","false","Biography information for Ruth George","High Peak","Ruth George","6334"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754081","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-09-06","<p>Implementation of the EU Water Framework Directive within the UK is a devolved matter.</p><p> </p><p>Updated River Basin Management Plans published in 2016 provide the framework for protecting and improving the water environment, and focus on the improvements for the period 2016 to 2021. The Plans for England confirm over £3billion of investment by 2021, leading to improvements in at least 680 water bodies. This includes an overall target to enhance at least 5000 miles of waters by 2021.</p><p> </p><p>The Plans will be reviewed and updated in 2021 taking account of progress that has been made and the best evidence then on what can be achieved by 2027.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-09-06T10:45:33.55Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754081/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754081/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754081/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-07-19","Water: EU Law","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what estimate he has made of the proportion of the UK's waterways that will meet the EU's good ecological and chemical status by 2027.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","6280"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754082","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-09-11","<p>We have already undertaken to review the UK Food Security Assessment. The Assessment covers all aspects of food security including international trade and global resource sustainability, so the scope is much wider than purely domestic production. The 2009/10 review concluded that we have a high degree of food security in the UK.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-09-11T16:04:05.673Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754082/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754082/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754082/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-07-19","Food Supply","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, if his Department will repeat the 2010 Food Security Assessment to inform thinking on the forthcoming Agriculture Bill.","false","Biography information for Mrs Emma Lewell-Buck","South Shields","Mrs Emma Lewell-Buck","6271"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754083","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-09-05","<p>This is a devolved matter.</p><p> </p><p>Hedgerows and verges play an important role in conserving and enhancing biodiversity. Most countryside hedgerows are legally protected and land managers in receipt of Basic Payment Scheme payments are required to protect hedgerows on their land. Through our agri-environment schemes such as Countryside Stewardship, we further recognise their valuable role by funding the management of hedgerows to deliver recognised benefits for wildlife, landscape and the historic environment.</p><p> </p><p>Local authorities and other public bodies (including county, district and parish councils) in England and Wales have a statutory duty, under section 40 of the Natural Environment and Rural Communities Act 2006, to consider the conservation of biodiversity in exercising their functions, including decisions on managing local roadside verges. Defra and the Welsh Assembly have issued guidance for local authorities and other public bodies on implementing their biodiversity duty.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-09-05T10:47:17.173Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754083/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754083/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754083/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-07-19","Hedges and Ditches","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps he is taking to preserve verges and hedgerows as valuable reserves for wildlife.","false","Biography information for Hywel Williams","Arfon","Hywel Williams","6013"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754084","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-09-05","<p>Local authorities have a critical role in achieving improvements in air quality. Under the Local Air Quality Management system, local authorities are required to review and assess air quality in their areas. They consider sources of pollution, including from transport . They designate Air Quality Management Areas and put in place Air Quality Action Plans to address air pollution issues where national air quality objectives are not being met.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-09-05T17:27:36.08Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754084/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754084/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754084/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-07-19","Transport: Exhaust Emissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, whether local authorities are required to consider the potential implications for air quality when making decisions on (a) permanent and (b) temporary transport schemes.","false","Biography information for Anneliese Dodds","Oxford East","Anneliese Dodds","6170"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754085","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-09-11","<p>Since 2008 the Environment Agency has made changes to over 270 abstraction licences to prevent over 27 billion litres of water per year being removed from the environment. This is enough water to supply half a million people, with water for one year.</p><p> </p><p>The government is updating its plan for managing abstraction and will publish in due course.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-09-11T15:55:11.963Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754085/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754085/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754085/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-07-19","Water Abstraction","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what the Government's policy is on preventing incidences of rivers drying up as a result of unsustainable water abstraction.","false","Biography information for Mrs Anne Main","St Albans","Mrs Anne Main","6068"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754086","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-09-05","<p>The application to reintroduce the Eurasian lynx to the Kielder Forest will be considered carefully in accordance with international guidelines and taking account of the impacts on affected communities, including public safety and the wider environment.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-09-05T10:41:18.563Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754086/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754086/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754086/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-07-19","Lynx: Kielder Forest","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment he has made of the potential safety risk to the public of reintroducing the Eurasian lynx to the Kielder Forest.","false","Biography information for Anne-Marie Trevelyan","Berwick-upon-Tweed","Mrs Anne-Marie Trevelyan","6163"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754087","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-09-05","<p>Once we leave the European Union, and in line with our manifesto commitment, we can take early steps to control the export of live farm animals for slaughter. We are currently considering options.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-09-05T11:07:53.477Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754087/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754087/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754087/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-07-19","Cattle: Exports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, whether he has plans to bring forward legislative proposals to ban the transport of live cattle overseas when the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Mrs Anne Main","St Albans","Mrs Anne Main","6162"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754088","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-09-11","<p>The Government has not conducted research specifically on the impact of roadworks on air quality. However, we recognise that while they are being carried out, roadworks can lead to congestion, which impacts on air quality as well as on people’s journeys. There are also emissions from the machinery used to carry out roadworks.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-09-11T16:53:10.327Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754088/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754088/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754088/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-07-19","Road Works: Air Pollution","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, whether research has been undertaken by the Government to examine the effect on air quality of roadworks; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Anneliese Dodds","Oxford East","Anneliese Dodds","6177"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754089","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-09-11","<p>Significant animal welfare concerns have not been raised with the Government in relation to feral cats although other concerns may apply. The Government considers that local authorities are best placed to consider local issues relating to the capture and relocation of feral cats. The Government strongly advises all cat owners to microchip their cats so that if their cats become lost or displaced there will be a much better chance that they will be re-united and not join the feral population.</p><p> </p><p>The Government recommends that owners should neuter their cats if they do not intend to breed from them, and ensure that they have appropriate inoculations as advised by a vet. These actions will help to reduce the chances of cats becoming stray and adding to the feral population, and should help reduce the spread of disease. In addition, some animal welfare charities run neutering schemes for feral cats to prevent their numbers increasing and spreading disease.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-09-11T16:01:00.987Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754089/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754089/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754089/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-07-19","Cats","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what policies his Department has put in place (a) for the capture and relocation of feral cats, (b) to tackle the overpopulation of feral cats and (c) to reduce the spread of diseases by feral cats.","false","Biography information for Lord Mann","Bassetlaw","John Mann","6203"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754090","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-09-11","<p>The next visit of Chagossians to Diego Garcia and the Outer Islands will take place from 30 October to 8 November. A programme of events on the island is being arranged. Those visitors who were born in either Peros Banhos or Salomon will spend two days visiting those groups of islands before rejoining the other group members on Diego Garcia.</p><p>We expect a further two visits to take place before April 2018. Each visit will accommodate twenty Chagossians, who will arrive into Diego Garcia by air and will return by the same route at the end of the visit.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2017-09-11T13:47:16.293Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754090/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754090/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754090/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-07-19","Diego Garcia: Ilois","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, when the next planned visit of Chagossians to Diego Garcia will take place; how many Chagossians will be able to take part in that visit; what the transport arrangements for that visit are; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Patrick Grady","Glasgow North","Patrick Grady","6152"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754091","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-09-07","<p>Chagossians can only visit the Territory as part of an official heritage visit. There are organised by the Foreign and Commonwealth Office and the Territory’s Administration.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2017-09-07T16:11:29.62Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754091/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754091/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754091/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-07-19","Diego Garcia: Ilois","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, under what circumstances Chagossians are allowed to visit the graves of their ancestors and East Point Plantation on Diego Garcia.","false","Biography information for Patrick Grady","Glasgow North","Patrick Grady","6153"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754092","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-09-11","<p>We recognise that there are human rights concerns in India-administered Kashmir. We encourage all States to ensure that their domestic laws are in line with international standards. Any allegations of human rights abuses must be investigated thoroughly, promptly and transparently. We have previously raised concerns, most recently by Foreign and Commonwealth Office Minister of State the Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon with Indian Minister of State for External Affairs M J Akbar during Lord Ahmad's visit to India in August 2017.</p>","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field",,"2017-09-11T15:24:34.433Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754092/answer","Biography information for Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754092/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754092/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-07-19","Kashmir: Human Rights","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent representations the Government has made to the Indian Government on reported human rights abuses in Kashmir.","false","Biography information for Jim McMahon","Oldham West and Royton","Jim McMahon","6109"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754093","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-09-07","<p>​The UK regularly engages with all relevant partners – including the government, parliament, political parties, the Electoral Commission, the National Human Rights Commission and civil society - to encourage them to put in place the necessary conditions for free and fair elections. The UK also funds programmes which support improvements to Uganda’s democratic governance, including election monitoring.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-09-07T13:11:32.03Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754093/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754093/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754093/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-07-19","Uganda: Politics and Government","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps his Department is taking to (a) promote free and fair elections and (b) support democratic institutions in Uganda.","false","Biography information for Mrs Pauline Latham","Mid Derbyshire","Pauline Latham","6114"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754096","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-09-11","<p>Both our Ambassador and Embassy officials regularly engage the Indonesian Government on issues relating to Papua in Jakarta and in the region itself. Our Ambassador and Embassy officials visit Papua periodically. Officials most recently visited in July and our Ambassador will visit again later this year.</p>","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field",,"2017-09-11T15:29:26.247Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754096/answer","Biography information for Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754096/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754096/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-07-19","Papua: Human Rights","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions his Department has had with the Indonesian Government on human rights violations in West Papua.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","6290"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754097","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-09-07","<p>Ministerial visits are under constant review. Our Embassies in Colombia and Venezuela continue to support and represent UK interests in those countries.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2017-09-07T16:27:00.673Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754097/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754097/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754097/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-07-19","Colombia and Venezuela: Visits Abroad","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what plans Ministers of his Department have to visit (a) Colombia and (b) Venezuela in the next 12 months.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","6265"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754098","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-09-07","<p>As part of our membership of the UN and EU, the UK imposes sanctions regimes relating to activity in Afghanistan, Belarus, Bosnia and Herzegovina, Burma, Burundi, Central African Republic, China, Democratic People's Republic of Korea (North Korea), Democratic Republic of Congo, Egypt, Eritrea, Iran, Iraq, Lebanon, Libya, Moldova, Republic of Guinea, Republic of Guinea-Bissau, Russia, Somalia, South Sudan, Sudan, Syria, Tunisia, Ukraine, Yemen and Zimbabwe.</p><p>The form of these sanctions regimes varies greatly. Further detail can be found via Her Majesty's Treasury and the Department for International Trade pages on the GOV.UK platform, in addition to publicly available information on the UN and EU websites.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2017-09-07T16:26:23.683Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754098/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754098/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754098/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-07-19","Sanctions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, which countries currently have sanctions imposed upon them as part of UN or EU obligations; and if he will publish what form those sanctions take.","false","Biography information for Dr David Drew","Stroud","Dr David Drew","6330"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754099","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-09-08","<p>​I raised our concerns over the issue of children in detention with the Israeli authorities during my recent visit to Israel between 22-23 August.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2017-09-08T10:56:14.133Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754099/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754099/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754099/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-07-19","Israel and Occupied Territories: Detainees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent discussions he has had with his Israeli counterpart about human rights violations committed against children in military custody in Israel and the Occupied Palestinian Territories.","false","Biography information for Kevin Hollinrake","Thirsk and Malton","Kevin Hollinrake","6272"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754100","Department of Health","false","2017-09-05","<p>As set out in Implementing the Five Year Forward View for Mental Health the expansion of Improving Access to Psychological Therapies services will focus on people with long term conditions, including neurological conditions such as Parkinson’s, and/or medically unexplained symptoms. New psychological therapy provision will see physical and mental health care provision co-located. Therapy will be integrated into existing medical pathways and services – either primary care, or secondary care services including neurology. The report can be viewed here:</p><p><a href="http://www.england.nhs.uk/mental-health/taskforce/imp/" target="_blank">www.england.nhs.uk/mental-health/taskforce/imp/</a></p><p>Although the majority of people with Parkinson’s can be cared for through routine access to primary and secondary care, NHS England commissions the specialised elements of Parkinson’s care that patients may receive from 24 specialised neurological treatment centres across England. Within these centres neurological multidisciplinary teams ensure patients can access a range of health professionals, including neurologists, neurosurgeons, clinical nurse specialists, psychologists, and that they can receive specialised treatment and support, according to their needs. Data from the National Health Service general practitioner survey has consistently indicated that people with neurological conditions, such as Parkinson’s, have the highest levels of anxiety and depression. This is an important issue and we are working with the Neurological Alliance who published a report on mental health and neurological conditions, Parity of esteem for people affected by neurological conditions: meeting the emotional, cognitive &amp; mental health needs of neurology patients on 5 July this year. The Neurology Advisory Group will ensure that there is system alignment and a national approach when considering the recommendations, which will be of benefit to patients. The Neurological Alliance report can be found at the following link:</p><p><a href="http://www.neural.org.uk/store/assets/files/696/original/Parity-of-esteem-for-people-affected-by-neuro-conditions-2017.pdf" target="_blank">www.neural.org.uk/store/assets/files/696/original/Parity-of-esteem-for-people-affected-by-neuro-conditions-2017.pdf</a></p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price","6034 ; 6262 ; 6310","2017-09-05T13:05:46.403Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754100/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754100/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754100/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-07-19","Parkinson's Disease: Depressive Illnesses","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what estimate his Department has made of the prevalence of (a) anxiety and (b) depression in people with Parkinson's.","false","Biography information for Mary Glindon","North Tyneside","Mary Glindon","6267"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754101","Department of Health","false","2017-09-06","<p>Information on the number of people diagnosed as being on the autism spectrum; the number of people on the autistic spectrum who have been diagnosed with having an anxiety disorder or depression; the number of people with autism who took their own lives, and the number of people with autism who have died within the requested timescales is not available centrally.</p><p> </p><p>We have made no assessment of the effectiveness of tools used in the diagnosis of autism in identifying co-existing mental health problems. The use of such tools is a matter for the clinicians concerned, taking into account relevant clinical guidance such as that published by the National Institute for Health and Care Excellence.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price","6042 ; 6045 ; 6046 ; 6269","2017-09-06T13:18:00.347Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754101/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754101/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754101/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-07-19","Autism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many people in England have been diagnosed as autistic.","false","Biography information for Luke Pollard","Plymouth, Sutton and Devonport","Luke Pollard","6268"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754102","Department of Health","false","2017-09-06","<p>Information on the number of people diagnosed as being on the autism spectrum; the number of people on the autistic spectrum who have been diagnosed with having an anxiety disorder or depression; the number of people with autism who took their own lives, and the number of people with autism who have died within the requested timescales is not available centrally.</p><p> </p><p>We have made no assessment of the effectiveness of tools used in the diagnosis of autism in identifying co-existing mental health problems. The use of such tools is a matter for the clinicians concerned, taking into account relevant clinical guidance such as that published by the National Institute for Health and Care Excellence.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price","6042 ; 6045 ; 6046 ; 6268","2017-09-06T13:18:00.583Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754102/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754102/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754102/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-07-19","Autism: Depressive Illnesses","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many autistic people were diagnosed with (a) an anxiety disorder and (b) depression in (i) 2016-17, (ii) 2015-16 and (iii) 2014-15.","false","Biography information for Luke Pollard","Plymouth, Sutton and Devonport","Luke Pollard","6269"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754103","Department of Health","false","2017-09-06","<p>When a person is assessed as eligible for NHS Continuing Healthcare (CHC) their assessed health and care needs are funded by their local clinical commissioning group.</p><p> </p><p>The total number of people eligible for CHC as at 31 March 2017 was 57,773. Of these 17,305 were assessed as eligible through the Fast Track Pathway Tool, and 40,468 through the standard CHC assessment process.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2017-09-06T14:02:17.553Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754103/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754103/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754103/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-07-19","Continuing Care","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many people receive NHS continuing healthcare provided by (a) a local government unit and (b) a clinical commissioning group.","false","Biography information for Mr Virendra Sharma","Ealing, Southall","Mr Virendra Sharma","6261"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754104","Department of Health","false","2017-09-11","<p>The amount the Department spent facilitating voluntary exits for staff in 2016-17 was £31,568,000.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-09-11T13:10:36.947Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754104/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754104/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754104/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-07-19","Department of Health: Redundancy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how much his Department spent facilitating voluntary exits for Department of Health staff in 2016-17; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mary Glindon","North Tyneside","Mary Glindon","6263"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754105","Department of Health","false","2017-09-11","<p>Current vacancies in the Department are a result of staff turnover and capability gaps within the new organisational structure. Roles that are currently vacant did not exist before the DH2020 programme and so were not filled by staff who left on voluntary exit.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-09-11T13:09:45.79Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754105/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754105/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754105/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-07-19","Department of Health: Vacancies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many of the current vacancies in his Department were previously filled by staff who took voluntary exits in 2016-17.","false","Biography information for Mary Glindon","North Tyneside","Mary Glindon","6264"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754106","Department of Health","false","2017-09-11","<p>The Framework Convention on Tobacco Control (FCTC) 2030 project has entered its second operational year and the Department has spent £3,955,369 to date.</p><p> </p><p>The FCTC Secretariat is required to produce a full evaluation report at the end of the five year life span of the project. The Department has published the following business case for the project. This is available at the following link:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/tobacco-control-measures-overseas" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/tobacco-control-measures-overseas</a></p><p>The Department of Health’s Official Development Assistance (ODA) spend is reported annually in the United Kingdom Government statistics on international development. The most up to date published information can be found in the 2016 provisional statistics produced by the Department for International Development in April 2017 at the following link:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/provisional-uk-official-development-assistance-as-a-proportion-of-gross-national-income-2016" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/provisional-uk-official-development-assistance-as-a-proportion-of-gross-national-income-2016</a></p><p>Table 3 shows a breakdown of UK Net ODA: by Government Department and Other Contributors of UK ODA, 2015 and 2016.</p><p> </p><p>In 2016, for the FCTC 2030 project, the Department spent £124,298 on a staff secondment to the World Health Organization and paid a £870,000 grant to the World Health Organization. The Department of Health’s administration costs are funded from a central ODA admin budget. The Department for International Development will publish final 2016 statistics on ODA in November 2017 which will contain a detailed breakdown of Department of Health’s ODA expenditure.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine","6297 ; 6303","2017-09-11T14:18:38.343Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754106/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754106/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754106/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-07-19","Smoking: Health Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how much of the funding committed by his Department to smoking cessation projects overseas has been spent to date.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","6291"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754107","Department of Health","false","2017-09-06","<p>Under the new arrangements for the appraisal and funding of cancer drugs introduced in July 2016, the National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) aims to publish draft recommendations on the use of all cancer drugs before licensing. Where NICE’s draft guidance recommends use of the drug for routine commissioning or for use through the Cancer Drugs Fund, NHS England will make Cancer Drugs Fund funding available for its use in National Health Service patients in line with NICE’s recommendations from the point of licensing. There should therefore be no gap in the availability of cancer drugs recommended by NICE that had previously been made available before licensing under the Early Access to Medicines Scheme.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2017-09-06T12:57:24.077Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754107/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754107/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754107/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-07-19","Cancer: Drugs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, when will companies following a recommendation for use from the Cancer Drugs Fund be able to access Cancer Drugs Fund funding for a drug which they have previously been making available to the NHS free of charge by means of the Early Access to Medicines Scheme.","false","Biography information for Mrs Pauline Latham","Mid Derbyshire","Pauline Latham","6302"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754108","Department of Health","false","2017-09-06","<p>The Government is committed to making prescriptions affordable to everyone, including to people who may need a large number of prescriptions. Whilst the standard prescription charge has been uplifted year on year to remain broadly in line with inflation and raise valuable revenue for the National Health Service, the Government took the decision to freeze the cost of the three-month and 12-month prescription prepayment certificates to support those with the greatest need.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2017-09-06T13:02:13.95Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754108/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754108/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754108/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-07-19","Prescriptions: Fees and Charges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, for what reasons the cost to the public of a Prescription Prepayment Certificate has remained at the same level while costs of individual prescriptions have risen.","false","Biography information for Alec Shelbrooke","Elmet and Rothwell","Alec Shelbrooke","6289"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754109","Department of Health","false","2017-09-05","<p>As set out in Implementing the Five Year Forward View for Mental Health the expansion of Improving Access to Psychological Therapies services will focus on people with long term conditions, including neurological conditions such as Parkinson’s, and/or medically unexplained symptoms. New psychological therapy provision will see physical and mental health care provision co-located. Therapy will be integrated into existing medical pathways and services – either primary care, or secondary care services including neurology. The report can be viewed here:</p><p><a href="http://www.england.nhs.uk/mental-health/taskforce/imp/" target="_blank">www.england.nhs.uk/mental-health/taskforce/imp/</a></p><p>Although the majority of people with Parkinson’s can be cared for through routine access to primary and secondary care, NHS England commissions the specialised elements of Parkinson’s care that patients may receive from 24 specialised neurological treatment centres across England. Within these centres neurological multidisciplinary teams ensure patients can access a range of health professionals, including neurologists, neurosurgeons, clinical nurse specialists, psychologists, and that they can receive specialised treatment and support, according to their needs. Data from the National Health Service general practitioner survey has consistently indicated that people with neurological conditions, such as Parkinson’s, have the highest levels of anxiety and depression. This is an important issue and we are working with the Neurological Alliance who published a report on mental health and neurological conditions, Parity of esteem for people affected by neurological conditions: meeting the emotional, cognitive &amp; mental health needs of neurology patients on 5 July this year. The Neurology Advisory Group will ensure that there is system alignment and a national approach when considering the recommendations, which will be of benefit to patients. The Neurological Alliance report can be found at the following link:</p><p><a href="http://www.neural.org.uk/store/assets/files/696/original/Parity-of-esteem-for-people-affected-by-neuro-conditions-2017.pdf" target="_blank">www.neural.org.uk/store/assets/files/696/original/Parity-of-esteem-for-people-affected-by-neuro-conditions-2017.pdf</a></p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price","6034 ; 6267 ; 6310","2017-09-05T13:05:46.357Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754109/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754109/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754109/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-07-19","Parkinson's Disease: Mental Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if his Department will invest in mental health services for people affected by Parkinson's.","false","Biography information for Mary Glindon","North Tyneside","Mary Glindon","6262"
