"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754191","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-09-07","<p>We collect global detainee statistics each year to provide a snapshot of the number of British nationals in detention overseas. We were aware of the following number of British nationals detained (either pre- or post- sentencing) across EU member states, at the snapshot date, in each of the requested years:</p><p>2010: 895</p><p>2011: 765</p><p>2013: 756</p><p>2014: 769</p><p>2015: 808</p><p>2016: 777</p><p> </p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2017-09-07T16:21:20.407Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754191/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754191/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754191/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-07-19","Prisoners: British Nationals Abroad","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how many UK citizens were serving custodial sentences in EU member states in (a) 2010, (b) 2011, (c) 2012, (d) 2013, (e) 2014, (f) 2015 and (g) 2016.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","6278"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754192","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-09-05","<p>Local stakeholders and the Hon. Member’s predecessor as the MP for Eastbourne were informed in April 2017 that the HMCTS Property Board had agreed alternative provision arrangements for Eastbourne.</p><p> </p><p>The courthouse at Eastbourne is expected to close in October 2017. The Eastbourne Traffic Commissioner’s Office will be used for hearings where appropriate. In addition, video link facilities for victims and witnesses will also be available at a local Police facility. Notice of closure has been provided to local legal stakeholders and is also displayed on public notices outside the building.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee","6273","2017-09-05T12:11:59.943Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754192/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754192/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754192/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-07-19","Courts: Eastbourne","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, if he will keep Eastbourne magistrates court, county court and family court open until alternative provision has been made.","false","Biography information for Stephen Lloyd","Eastbourne","Stephen Lloyd","6274"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754193","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-09-05","<p>Applications to the Exceptional Case Funding scheme for immigration matters, <br>by age of applicant, April 2016 to March 2017</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>FY application received</p></td><td><p>Under 18</p></td><td><p>18-24</p></td><td><p>25 and over</p></td><td><p>Unknown</p></td><td><p>Total</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Apr 2016 - Mar 2017</p></td><td><p>63</p></td><td><p>127</p></td><td><p>807</p></td><td><p>10</p></td><td><p>1,007</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><br> <br>Applications to the Exceptional Case Funding scheme for immigration matters, <br>which were granted1, by age of applicant, April 2016 to March 2017</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>FY application received</p></td><td><p>Under 18</p></td><td><p>18-24</p></td><td><p>25 and over</p></td><td><p>Unknown</p></td><td><p>Total</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Apr 2016 - Mar 2017</p></td><td><p>44</p></td><td><p>98</p></td><td><p>541</p></td><td><p>5</p></td><td><p>688</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><br>1 Granted by 31 May 2017</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2017-09-05T12:13:22.367Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754193/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754193/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754193/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-07-19","Immigration: Legal Aid Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many children under 18 (a) applied for and (b) were granted legal aid through the Exceptional Case Funding Scheme in immigration cases in 2016-17.","false","Biography information for Kate Green","Stretford and Urmston","Kate Green","6305"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754194","Leader of the House","false","2017-09-08","<p>Short Money is funding to assist an opposition party in carrying out its Parliamentary business.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>Under the resolution of the House of 26 May 1999, financial assistance is not provided to independent Members of Parliament.</p><p>It is the Government’s view that this issue of Short Money for independent Members of Parliament is primarily a matter for the House itself to resolve.</p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2017-09-08T16:29:22.343Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754194/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754194/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754194/answer",,,,,"34","Leader of the House","Leader of the House","2017-07-19","Short Money","1","House of Commons","To ask the Leader of the House, if she will amend the Resolution on Short Money to support independent members of Parliament who have sworn the oath; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Lady Hermon","North Down","Lady Hermon","6154"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754195","Northern Ireland Office","false","2017-09-05","<p>Salaries and allowances for Members of the Northern Ireland Assembly are the responsibility of the Assembly and, under the Assembly Members (Independent Financial Review and Standards) Act (Northern Ireland) 2011, are determined by the Independent Financial Review Panel. Any change to this arrangement at Westminster would require primary legislation. The Government’s overriding priority remains supporting the restoration of devolved government, as Northern Ireland’s future is best served by local decision-making based on partnership and agreement.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2017-09-05T09:52:25.767Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754195/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754195/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754195/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2017-07-19","Devolution: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, pursuant to the Answer of 10 July 2017 to Question 2967, which devolved authority has responsibility for salaries and allowances in the absence of a Northern Ireland Assembly; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Lady Hermon","North Down","Lady Hermon","6155"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754196","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-05","<p>The proportion of Cabinet Office annual expenditure allocated to work relating to the UK’s exit from the UK is not held centrally and could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-09-05T13:46:33.64Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754196/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754196/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754196/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-07-19","Prime Minister: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how much and what proportion of his Office's expenditure has been identified as relating to its work on the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Hywel Williams","Arfon","Hywel Williams","6027"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754197","Scotland Office","false","2017-09-06","<p>The UK has a strong small satellite manufacturing sector, and forecasts suggest that the global satellite launch and spaceflight industry could be worth as much as £25 billion pounds over the next 20 years. By establishing a spaceport to enable these activities, growth and skilled jobs will be created in regions of the UK that need them most.</p><p> </p><p>The UK Space Agency is leading work across Government to enable the UK to play a leading part in the growing commercial space market. As part of this programme, the Space Agency is working with a number of different sites across the UK that have expressed interest in becoming a spaceport, and have recently invited proposals from partnerships of potential spaceports and space vehicle operators.</p><p> </p><p>Glasgow Prestwick Airport in Ayrshire has been looking into starting spaceport operations for some years now, working closely with the Space Agency to develop their plans. Any proposal for a UK spaceport will be assessed on both value for money and benefit – both local and national. I cannot discuss the details or identities of any bids as this is an on-going commercial process, but I will update the hon Member as soon as possible.</p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2017-09-06T13:10:45.903Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754197/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754197/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754197/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2017-07-19","Space Technology: Ayrshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, what assessment he has made of the potential effect on the local economy of the construction and establishment of a UK spaceport in Ayrshire.","false","Biography information for Bill Grant","Ayr, Carrick and Cumnock","Bill Grant","6023"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754198","Scotland Office","false","2017-09-05","<p>I have had a range of meetings with business and local representatives about supporting economic growth in Ayrshire, covering individual projects within a proposed Ayrshire Growth Deal and looking at how the UK’s Industrial Strategy will deliver for Ayrshire.</p><p> </p><p>In a significant step, on 9 August I was pleased to announce £3.5 million UK government investment to support the HALO project in Kilmarnock. This is a vital project that will strengthen Ayrshire’s economic prospects, create nearly 1000 jobs and benefit local businesses and residents.</p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2017-09-05T11:51:06.487Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754198/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754198/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754198/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2017-07-19","Local Growth Deals: Ayrshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, what discussions he has had with business and local representatives on the Ayrshire Growth Deal.","false","Biography information for Bill Grant","Ayr, Carrick and Cumnock","Bill Grant","6024"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754199","Scotland Office","false","2017-09-05","<p>The proposals agreed under the Edinburgh and South East Scotland City Region Deal were all originated by the Deal partners and I can confirm that it was not a project put forward by the local partners as part of the Edinburgh and South East Scotland City Deal.</p><p> </p><p>The UK Government’s contributions to City Deals focus on projects that fall in reserved policy areas. Transport policy is a devolved matter and within the City Deal, the rail link would have been an investment for the Scottish Government to consider.</p><p> </p><p>Any future investment in the rail link would be a decision for the Scottish Government, who have responsibility for rail investment in Scotland.</p><p> </p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2017-09-05T11:53:11.383Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754199/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754199/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754199/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2017-07-19","Railways: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, what discussions he has had with Cabinet colleagues on funding for reinstatement of the Levenmouth Rail Link as part of the Edinburgh and South East Scotland City Region bid.","false","Biography information for Peter Grant","Glenrothes","Peter Grant","6236"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754200","Scotland Office","false","2017-09-06","<p>Nothing has been spent on any of these advertising channels in the period in question.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2017-09-06T13:21:45.503Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754200/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754200/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754200/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2017-07-19","Scotland Office: Advertising","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, what his Department spent on advertising other than on social media in each month since January 2016; and how much of that spending was on (a) newspaper, (b) magazine, (c) billboard or similar, (d) radio, (e) television and (f) cinema advertising.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre  Brock","6288"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754201","Scotland Office","false","2017-09-06","<p>Agencies are procured as and when required and are not held on a retainer basis. We do not currently contract any services for advertising.</p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2017-09-06T13:22:42.317Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754201/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754201/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754201/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2017-07-19","Scotland Office: Advertising","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, what external advisers or companies his Department uses for advertising.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre  Brock","6287"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754202","Scotland Office","false","2017-09-06","<p>Information on staffing, including a breakdown of staff by grade and gender, is published in the Scotland Office Annual Report:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/633804/Scotland_Office_AR_2016-17_web__2_.pdf" target="_blank">Scotland Office Annual Report 2016/17</a></p><p>A detailed list of job titles and number of staff by each job title not published, as to do so would potentially make staff identifiable when numbers are less than five.</p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2017-09-06T13:20:52.27Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754202/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754202/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754202/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2017-07-19","Scotland Office: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, if he will list the job titles and numbers of staff under each job title in his Department.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre  Brock","6194"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754203","Scotland Office","false","2017-09-06","<p>The UK Government continues to press ahead with discussions with the Tay City partners and I can confirm that further talks took place at the end of August.</p><p> </p><p>Local partners have put forward a large number of proposals, and the next step is to scrutinise these proposals rigorously to identify together which can deliver transformational change for the economy of the Tay Cities region.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell","6424","2017-09-06T13:13:16.743Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754203/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754203/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754203/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2017-07-19","Devolution: Tayside","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, what recent progress has been made on the Tay City Deal.","false","Biography information for Luke Graham","Ochil and South Perthshire","Luke Graham","6223"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754204","Scotland Office","false","2017-09-06","<p>Following my meeting with the hon Gentleman and the MP for Stirling, on 4 August I met with the Leader of Stirling Council and his officials to discuss progress with the Deal.</p><p> </p><p>My officials followed up by meeting Stirling and Clackmannanshire Councils on 29 August. We are keen to reach agreement on the terms of an ambitious Deal as soon as possible, recognising this will require intensive engagement by the local partners.</p><p> </p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2017-09-06T13:16:15.913Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754204/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754204/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754204/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2017-07-19","Devolution: Stirling and Clackmannanshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, what recent progress has been made on the Stirling and Clackmannanshire City Deal.","false","Biography information for Luke Graham","Ochil and South Perthshire","Luke Graham","6224"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754206","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-08","<p>In formulating plans for the next Control Period, the Transport Secretary has looked to balance a wide range of factors, including affordability and supply chain capability.</p><p> </p><p>We are acutely aware of the reliance of the railway on specialist resource held within the supply chain, and wish to ensure that funding is distributed appropriately to support the efficient delivery of CP6.</p><p> </p><p>As set out in the High Level Output Specification the Transport Secretary expects Network Rail to increase its efficiency and delivery capability across its portfolio of work during the Control Period and expects a strong and robust challenge from the independent economic Regulator (ORR), in its calculation of the efficiency of spend as part of the wider Periodic Review (PR18) process.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-09-08T10:19:18.77Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754206/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754206/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754206/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-07-19","Railways: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment he has made of the potential extra cost to projects in Control Period 6 and beyond in the event that the railway supply chain receives an insufficient volume of orders to be able to maintain its skilled workers.","false","Biography information for Stephen Hammond","Wimbledon","Stephen Hammond","6025"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754207","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-08","<p>The Department’s analysis of the Strategic Outline Business Case for Crossrail 2 is one strand of the work we are currently progressing to inform decisions on the scheme, including on the appropriate timings of any public consultation. It sits alongside the work we have recently agreed with the Mayor of London to examine ways to improve affordability ahead of this autumn’s Budget.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-09-08T11:46:27.103Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754207/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754207/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754207/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-07-19","Crossrail 2 Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 28 June 2017 to Question 204, on Crossrail 2 Line, what the timescale is for the analysis referred to; and when the date of the next stage of the public consultation will be announced.","false","Biography information for Stephen Hammond","Wimbledon","Stephen Hammond","6043"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754208","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-05","<p>The Government recognises the case for capacity improvements in London and the wider South East, such as those that Crossrail 2 could deliver. We are currently analysing the Strategic Outline Business Case, submitted by Transport for London, to ensure it is a robust investment with a fair and credible funding plan. This sits alongside the work we have recently agreed with the Mayor of London to examine ways to improve affordability ahead of this autumn’s Budget. Our next steps to deliver those capacity improvements will be decided when these strands of work are complete.</p><p> </p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-09-05T16:20:53.183Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754208/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754208/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754208/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-07-19","Crossrail 2 Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, when he expects to announce his decision on the business case submitted by Transport for London for Crossrail 2.","false","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","Chipping Barnet","Theresa Villiers","6129"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754209","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-08","<p>An announcement was made on 28<sup>th</sup> July 2017. The 5 successful bids for funds under the New Stations Fund scheme were:</p><p> </p><p>Bow Street (Wales), Portway Parkway (Bristol), Warrington West (Warrington), Horden Peterlee (North East England), Reading Green Park (Berkshire).</p><p> </p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-09-08T11:19:09.857Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754209/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754209/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754209/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-07-19","Railway Stations: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what the timetable is for the announcement of successful bids to the New Station Fund.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","6217"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754210","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-11","<p>The Government is now considering the responses to the airspace consultation and we plan to publish our response in the autumn.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-09-11T09:09:13.34Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754210/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754210/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754210/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-07-19","Air Traffic Control","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, when he plans to publish his Department's new airspace plan.","false","Biography information for Steve Double","St Austell and Newquay","Steve Double","6215"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754211","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-08","<p>The Government’s policy on concessionary bus travel remains unchanged, though my Department continues to engage on this issue on a regular basis with the Department for Work and Pensions and other Government Departments as well as local authorities and the transport sector.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-09-08T09:53:24.63Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754211/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754211/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754211/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-07-19","Bus Services: Concessions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, with reference to the Answer of 20 April 2017 to Question 70590, on bus services: concessions, whether it remains his Department's policy to not extend the statutory scheme to include peak travel.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","6181"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754212","Home Office","false","2017-09-05","<p>Table 1 - average sampled passenger wait time for Gatwick (North and South) from 1 July 2016 until 30 June 2017.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Date</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>EEA</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Non EEA</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Total</strong></p></td><td><p>00:05:40</p></td><td><p>00:12:07</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>The information provided relates to passenger queuing times – defined as when a passenger arrives at the UK Border control desk - and as such excludes transaction times for clearance. Performance is assessed over a 12 month period.</p><p> </p><p>The performance against service levels is assessed over a month period. If 95% or above of passenger wait times sampled are recorded as within the 25 minute (EEA) and 45 minute (non EEA) service standard, the service level is assessed as met, if less than 95%, then this is considered a breach of the service level.</p><p> </p><p>This is provisional management information that is subject to change. It has not been assured to the standard of Official Statistics.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-09-05T08:02:05.833Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754212/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754212/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754212/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-19","Gatwick Airport","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what the average queuing time at Gatwick Airport is.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","6122"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754213","Home Office","false","2017-09-05","<p>Table 1 - the average sampled passenger wait time for Heathrow (Terminal 2, 3, 4 and 5) from 1 July 2016 until 30 June 2017.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Date</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>EEA</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Non EEA</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Total</strong></p></td><td><p>00:03:46</p></td><td><p>00:17:38</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Notes</p><p> </p><p>No data for Heathrow Terminal 1 as terminal closed in 2015.</p><p> </p><p>The information provided relates to passenger queuing times – defined as when a passenger arrives at the UK Border control desk - and as such excludes transaction times for clearance. Performance is assessed over a 12 month period.</p><p> </p><p>The performance against service levels is assessed over a month period. If 95% or above of passenger wait times sampled are recorded as within the 25 minute (EEA) and 45 minute (non EEA) service standard, the service level is assessed as met, if less than 95%, then this is considered a breach of the service level.</p><p> </p><p><em>This is provisional management information that is subject to change. It has not been assured to the standard of Official Statistics.</em></p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-09-05T08:02:33.737Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754213/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754213/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754213/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-19","Heathrow Airport","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what the average queuing time at London Heathrow Airport is.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","6123"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754214","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-08","<p>eCall will be required in all new types of cars and light commercial vehicles approved from 31 March 2018 in accordance with the EU regulation 2015/758.</p><p> </p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-09-08T09:44:17.13Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754214/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754214/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754214/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-07-19","Roads: Accidents","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what progress has been made on implementing eCall in all new vehicles in the UK by April 2018.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","6213"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754215","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-08","<p>Highways England continues to improve the clearance times of incidents on the strategic road network. The duration of closures is closely monitored, with the aim to clear 85% of live lane incidents on motorways within 60 minutes. All incidents that fail this target are analysed to see where lessons can be learned. For the 2016-17 period Highways England achieved 85.93% and have subsequently set a new internal target of 87% for the 2017/18, demonstrating their continued determination to reduce delays and improve journeys for road users.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-09-08T10:56:16.683Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754215/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754215/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754215/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-07-19","Roads: Closures","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether his Department is taking steps to reduce the length of closures which occur on major roads and motorways after a collision; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","Chipping Barnet","Theresa Villiers","6171"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754216","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-11","<p>The Government does not propose to publish a formal response to the Peninsula Rail Task Force (PRTF) report at the present time as we continue to engage with the PRTF and other interested parties as the planning for Network Rail’s work programme for the period starting in April 2019 and the development of the specifications for the future Great Western and Cross Country franchises unfold.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard","6252","2017-09-11T15:59:04.903Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754216/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754216/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754216/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-07-19","Railways: South West","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, when the Government intends to respond formally to the Peninsula Rail Task Force rail improvement plan submitted in 2016.","false","Biography information for Sir Gary Streeter","South West Devon","Mr Gary Streeter","6120"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754217","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-05","<p>Flexible multi-buy tickets give people who commute part-time a better deal than they would otherwise have access to. We have challenged the rail industry to develop proposals for pricing, and delivering more flexible ticketing options, for those who work or commute part-time, which could also attract new customers onto the railway. The Department has made early assessments with operators on the effect of the introduction of these types of tickets on fares revenue, and continues to review this policy going forward.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-09-05T16:26:13.26Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754217/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754217/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754217/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-07-19","Railways: Season Tickets","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment he has made of the potential effect of the introduction of part-time season tickets on train fare revenue.","false","Biography information for Andy McDonald","Middlesbrough","Andy McDonald","6132"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754218","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-11","<p>The Mayor of London has recently written to the Secretary of State for Transport requesting a reform of the law to give Transport for London the power to cap the number of private hire vehicle driver licences. The Mayor requested this reform as part of a wider package of measures which the Secretary of State has asked him to provide details of, sharing how the proposal would work in practice.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-09-11T10:27:47.653Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754218/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754218/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754218/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-07-19","Taxis: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will take steps to cap private hire licensing by Transport for London to reduce cross border-hiring.","false","Biography information for Mrs Anne Main","St Albans","Mrs Anne Main","6067"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754219","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-11","<p>The Government does not propose to publish a formal response to the Peninsula Rail Task Force (PRTF) report at the present time as we continue to engage with the PRTF and other interested parties as the planning for Network Rail’s work programme for the period starting in April 2019 and the development of the specifications for the future Great Western and Cross Country franchises unfold.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard","6120","2017-09-11T15:59:04.967Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754219/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754219/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754219/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-07-19","Railways: South West","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether the Government plans to publish a response to the Peninsula Rail Task Force rail improvement plan submitted in 2016.","false","Biography information for Sir Gary Streeter","South West Devon","Mr Gary Streeter","6252"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754221","Wales Office","false","2017-09-05","<p>The Supreme Court has been clear that the devolved legislatures do not have a veto over the UK’s withdrawal from the EU. The Government is committed to positive engagement with the devolved administrations to ensure that withdrawal from the EU is a successful and smooth process for the whole of the UK.</p><p> </p><p>The Government is seeking the consent of the National Assembly for Wales and the other devolved legislatures for the European Union (Withdrawal) Bill.</p>","Vale of Glamorgan","Alun Cairns",,"2017-09-05T10:41:35.813Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754221/answer","Biography information for Alun Cairns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754221/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754221/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2017-07-19","European Union (Notification of Withdrawal) Bill: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, what legal advice he has sought on whether a Legislative Consent Motion is required from the Welsh Assembly before the European Union (Notification of Withdrawal) Act 2017 becomes law.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","6318"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754222","Wales Office","false","2017-09-05","<p>The UK Government is keen to encourage any schemes which help to increase participation rates of children in sport. However this is a devolved issue in Wales and therefore the responsibility of the Welsh Government.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Vale of Glamorgan","Alun Cairns",,"2017-09-05T10:42:39.613Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754222/answer","Biography information for Alun Cairns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754222/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754222/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2017-07-19","Sport: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, what discussions he has had with the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport on increasing participation rates of children in Wales in sport.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","6276"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754223","Wales Office","false","2017-09-05","<p>With 750 miles of coastline, Wales is perfectly placed to exploit energy from our tides through a variety of developing technologies, including tidal stream or wave turbines. In addition, the UK Government is currently considering the role tidal lagoons could play in the UK’s energy mix.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Vale of Glamorgan","Alun Cairns",,"2017-09-05T10:43:47.36Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754223/answer","Biography information for Alun Cairns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754223/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754223/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2017-07-19","Tidal Power: Cardiff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, what steps his Department is taking to promote renewable energy through tidal power in Cardiff Central constituency.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","6277"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754224","Wales Office","false","2017-09-05","<p>The Home Secretary and I have regular discussions on a range of issues.</p><p>The Government has made clear that there should be no safe space online for terrorists and their supporters to radicalise, recruit, incite, or inspire. We are supporting community-based initiatives that challenge Daesh’s core communications and provide credible counter narratives.</p><p>The Prevent Programme is fundamentally about safeguarding and supporting vulnerable individuals to stop them becoming terrorists or supporting terrorism. It works best when delivered in partnership with communities. In the last year, we have considerably increased our programme of Prevent activity through our network of Prevent professionals.</p>","Vale of Glamorgan","Alun Cairns",,"2017-09-05T10:45:12.16Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754224/answer","Biography information for Alun Cairns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754224/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754224/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2017-07-19","Radicalism: Cardiff Central","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, if he will discuss the effectiveness of the deradicalisation programme in Cardiff Central constituency with the Home Secretary.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","6321"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754225","Wales Office","false","2017-09-05","<p>The UK Government is keen to encourage any schemes which will increase the participation rates of children in sport and which may also help to tackle mental health issues. However, both of these matters are devolved and therefore the responsibility of the Welsh Government.</p>","Vale of Glamorgan","Alun Cairns",,"2017-09-05T10:47:46.027Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754225/answer","Biography information for Alun Cairns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754225/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754225/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2017-07-19","Mental Health Services: Neath","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, what discussions he has had with the Secretary of State for Health on the adequacy of provision of sport in Neath constituency to help to tackle mental health issues in primary aged children.","false","Biography information for Christina Rees","Neath","Christina Rees","6190"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754226","Wales Office","false","2017-09-05","<p>There is no single pathway to radicalisation for Islamist inspired, Far Right, or any other form of terrorism, and our radicalisation model applies to all forms of terrorism.</p><p> </p><p>The introduction of the Prevent Duty has embedded consideration of the risk of radicalisation in the day-to-day work of frontline statutory partners. It covers schools, colleges, universities, health, local authorities, police and prisons.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>142 community based projects were delivered in the UK in 2015/16 reaching over 42,000 participants. Over half of these projects were delivered in schools, aimed at increasing young people’s resilience to terrorist and extremist ideologies.</p><p> </p>","Vale of Glamorgan","Alun Cairns",,"2017-09-05T10:49:09.967Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754226/answer","Biography information for Alun Cairns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754226/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754226/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2017-07-19","Radicalism: Neath","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, what steps he is taking to protect children in Neath constituency who are at risk of radicalisation.","false","Biography information for Christina Rees","Neath","Christina Rees","6196"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754227","Wales Office","false","2017-09-05","<p>With 750 miles of coastline, Wales is perfectly placed to exploit energy from our tides through a variety of developing technologies, including tidal stream or wave turbines. In addition, the UK Government is currently considering the role tidal lagoons could play in the UK’s energy mix.</p>","Vale of Glamorgan","Alun Cairns","6198","2017-09-05T10:51:29.943Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754227/answer","Biography information for Alun Cairns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754227/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754227/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2017-07-19","Tidal Power: Vale of Clwyd","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, what steps the Government is taking to promote renewable energy through tidal power in the Vale of Clwyd.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","6294"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754228","Wales Office","false","2017-09-05","<p>Policy on the promotion of marine life in Wales is the responsibility of the Welsh Government and the National Assembly for Wales.</p>","Vale of Glamorgan","Alun Cairns",,"2017-09-05T10:54:08.107Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754228/answer","Biography information for Alun Cairns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754228/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754228/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2017-07-19","Marine Environment: Vale of Clwyd","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, what recent steps the Government has taken to promote marine life in the Vale of Clwyd.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","6292"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754229","Wales Office","false","2017-09-05","<p>With 750 miles of coastline, Wales is perfectly placed to exploit energy from our tides through a variety of developing technologies, including tidal stream or wave turbines. In addition, the UK Government is currently considering the role tidal lagoons could play in the UK’s energy mix.</p>","Vale of Glamorgan","Alun Cairns","6294","2017-09-05T10:51:30.007Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754229/answer","Biography information for Alun Cairns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754229/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754229/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2017-07-19","Tidal Power: Vale of Clwyd","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, what steps his Department is taking to promote tidal power in the Vale of Clwyd as a source of renewable energy.","false","Biography information for Christina Rees","Neath","Christina Rees","6198"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754230","Wales Office","false","2017-09-05","<p>The Home Secretary and I have regular discussions on a range of issues.</p><p>The Government has made clear that there should be no safe space online for terrorists and their supporters to radicalise, recruit, incite, or inspire. We are supporting community-based initiatives that challenge Daesh’s core communications and provide credible counter narratives.</p><p>The Prevent Programme is fundamentally about safeguarding and supporting vulnerable individuals to stop them becoming terrorists or supporting terrorism. It works best when delivered in partnership with communities. In the last year, we have considerably increased our programme of Prevent activity through our network of Prevent professionals.</p>","Vale of Glamorgan","Alun Cairns",,"2017-09-05T10:55:15.013Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754230/answer","Biography information for Alun Cairns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754230/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754230/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2017-07-19","Radicalism: Neath","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, what discussions he has had with the Home Secretary on the effectiveness of the Government's de-radicalisation programmes in Neath constituency.","false","Biography information for Christina Rees","Neath","Christina Rees","6197"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754231","Wales Office","false","2017-09-05","<p>The UK Government is committed to supporting our veterans through the Armed Forces Covenant. However, many of the services covered by the covenant, including the provision of and access to local sporting facilities, are devolved and therefore the responsibility of the Welsh Government.</p><p> </p>","Vale of Glamorgan","Alun Cairns",,"2017-09-05T10:56:29.643Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754231/answer","Biography information for Alun Cairns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754231/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754231/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2017-07-19","Veterans: Neath","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, what recent discussions he has had with the Secretary of State for Defence on the availability of sporting facilities for former service personnel with disabilities in Neath constituency.","false","Biography information for Christina Rees","Neath","Christina Rees","6186"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754232","Women and Equalities","false","2017-09-05","<p>This Government is committed to LGBT equality throughout the United Kingdom and that is why we are proud to have introduced marriage for same sex couples in England and Wales. We recently announced the launch of a National LGBT Survey asking LGBT people about their experiences of accessing public services, and our intention to consult on reforming the Gender Recognition Act 2004.</p><p> </p><p>Equalities policy is a devolved matter so improving services and support for LGBT people locally would be the responsibility of the Welsh Government.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-09-05T13:05:32.06Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754232/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754232/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754232/answer",,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2017-07-19","LGBT People: Neath","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, what recent steps she has taken to remove barriers to inclusivity for LGBT individuals in Neath constituency.","false","Biography information for Christina Rees","Neath","Christina Rees","6189"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754233","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-06","<p>Developing a workable and sustainable funding model for supported housing is a priority for the Government. We will set out further details on the Government’s plans in the autumn.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage","6221","2017-09-06T10:31:11.897Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754233/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754233/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754233/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-07-19","Housing Benefit: Supported Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, with reference to the Written Ministerial Statement of 15 September 2016 on housing benefit, what estimate he has made of the size of the top-up fund for supported accommodation.","false","Biography information for Kate Green","Stretford and Urmston","Kate Green","6220"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754234","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-06","<p>Developing a workable and sustainable funding model for supported housing is a priority for the Government. We will set out further details on the Government’s plans in the autumn.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage","6220","2017-09-06T10:31:11.943Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754234/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754234/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754234/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-07-19","Housing Benefit: Supported Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, with reference to the Written Ministerial Statement of 15 September 2016 HCWS154, what progress has been made on the administration of the supported accommodation top-up fund.","false","Biography information for Kate Green","Stretford and Urmston","Kate Green","6221"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754235","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-06","<p>The department has not set a target for upholding original decisions at Mandatory Reconsideration. The 80 per cent figure, which was used in the answer to Freedom of Information request 1740, is not considered by the decision maker when they carry out a Mandatory Reconsideration but is used to assess the quality of benefit decisions. In order to ensure we have consistently accurate decisions we track and monitor Mandatory Reconsiderations to assess the quality of our initial decision making and to help understand and improve our processes.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-09-06T10:29:48.393Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754235/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754235/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754235/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-07-19","Social Security Benefits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, with reference to his Department's freedom of information response 1740 of 15 May 2017, what factors his Department took into consideration in setting the 80 per cent of the original decisions are to be upheld measure for monitoring mandatory reconsideration; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","6159"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754236","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-05","<p>DWP are currently undertaking work, in conjunction with Curo Group, a housing association based in the South West, to investigate and understand the true level of rent arrears for their tenants, what is causing them and any impacts Universal Credit may be having. We will consider how nationally representative the analyses are and whether and how it should be expanded.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds","6232 ; 6233","2017-09-05T11:05:20.76Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754236/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754236/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754236/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-07-19","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will include research from Scotland in his Department's examination of universal credit and rent arrears.","false","Biography information for Dr Philippa Whitford","Central Ayrshire","Dr Philippa Whitford","6234"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754237","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-05","<p>The Universal Credit full service is due to rollout in Coventry in April 2018.</p><p> </p><p>A full rollout schedule has been published and is available at the following link:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/628958/universal-credit-transition-rollout-schedule.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/628958/universal-credit-transition-rollout-schedule.pdf</a></p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-09-05T11:07:40.15Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754237/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754237/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754237/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-07-19","Universal Credit: Coventry","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what the timetable is for roll-out of universal credit in Coventry.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","6241"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754238","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-05","<p>DWP are currently undertaking work, in conjunction with Curo Group, a housing association based in the South West, to investigate and understand the true level of rent arrears for their tenants, what is causing them and any impacts Universal Credit may be having. We will consider how nationally representative the analyses are and whether and how it should be expanded.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds","6233 ; 6234","2017-09-05T11:05:20.65Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754238/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754238/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754238/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-07-19","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, when his Department's examination of rent arrears and universal credit will be completed.","false","Biography information for Dr Philippa Whitford","Central Ayrshire","Dr Philippa Whitford","6232"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754239","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-05","<p>DWP are currently undertaking work, in conjunction with Curo Group, a housing association based in the South West, to investigate and understand the true level of rent arrears for their tenants, what is causing them and any impacts Universal Credit may be having. We will consider how nationally representative the analyses are and whether and how it should be expanded.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds","6232 ; 6234","2017-09-05T11:05:20.713Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754239/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754239/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754239/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-07-19","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, with which housing associations his Department is working to investigate rent arrears in universal credit.","false","Biography information for Dr Philippa Whitford","Central Ayrshire","Dr Philippa Whitford","6233"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754240","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-06","<p>Employment and Support Allowance (ESA) was introduced in October 2008.</p><p>The available information is shown in the following tables:</p><p> </p><p><strong>Table 1: Number of individuals making an initial claim to Employment and Support Allowance (ESA) whose main disabling condition was recorded as Crohn’s Disease or Ulcerative Colitis, Great Britain, 2008 - 2016</strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong> Year of ESA claim start</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Initial ESA<br> claims</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2008 (Oct – Dec)</strong></p></td><td><p>300</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2009</strong></p></td><td><p>2,200</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2010</strong></p></td><td><p>2,200</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2011</strong></p></td><td><p>2,600</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2012</strong></p></td><td><p>2,800</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2013</strong></p></td><td><p>2,700</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2014</strong></p></td><td><p>2,800</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2015</strong></p></td><td><p>2,600</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2016 (Jan - Sep)</strong></p></td><td><p>1,800</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p><strong>Table 2: Number of individuals assigned to ESA Support Group or the ESA Work Capability Group following their Work Capability Assessment (for initial, repeat or IB reassessment claims), whose main disabling condition was recorded as Crohn’s Disease or Ulcerative Colitis, Great Britain, 2008 - 2016</strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Year of ESA claim start </strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Initial ESA<br> claims</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Repeat ESA<br> assessments</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>IB<br> reassessments</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2008 (Oct – Dec)</strong></p></td><td><p>100</p></td><td><p>100</p></td><td><p>.</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2009</strong></p></td><td><p>700</p></td><td><p>600</p></td><td><p>.</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2010</strong></p></td><td><p>800</p></td><td><p>700</p></td><td><p>.</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2011</strong></p></td><td><p>1,100</p></td><td><p>1,300</p></td><td><p>1,300</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2012</strong></p></td><td><p>1,600</p></td><td><p>1,900</p></td><td><p>2,300</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2013</strong></p></td><td><p>1,200</p></td><td><p>1,000</p></td><td><p>1,800</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2014</strong></p></td><td><p>1,200</p></td><td><p>400</p></td><td><p>200</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2015</strong></p></td><td><p>1,200</p></td><td><p>300</p></td><td><p>100</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2016 (Jan - Sep)</strong></p></td><td><p>700</p></td><td><p>-</p></td><td><p>-</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p><strong>Source for Tables 1 and 2:</strong> Application data is derived from administrative data held by the DWP and assessment data provided by the Healthcare Provider.</p><p> </p><p><strong>Notes for Tables 1 and 2:</strong></p><ol><li>The figures are rounded to the nearest 100. ‘–‘denotes figures that are zero or less than 50. ‘.’ denotes not applicable.</li><li>The information for 2016 is provided up to September 2016 only; this is the latest data available at time of request.</li><li>Data is available for ESA from October 2008 and for IB reassessment claims from April 2011.</li><li>An individual may have made more than one ESA claim or assessment in any given year. These individuals will only be counted once in each of the figures provided.</li><li>The primary medical condition recorded on the claim form does not itself confer entitlement to ESA. So, for example, a decision on entitlement for a customer claiming ESA on the basis of Crohn’s disease or Ulcerative Colitis would be based on their ability to carry out the range of activities assessed by the work capability assessment.</li></ol>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-09-06T10:16:44.107Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754240/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754240/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754240/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-07-19","Employment and Support Allowance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people have (a) applied for and (b) received employment and support allowance, whose main disabling condition was recorded as Crohn's disease or ulcerative colitis, in each of the last 10 years.","false","Biography information for Mrs Anne Main","St Albans","Mrs Anne Main","6069"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754241","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-06","<p>Between April 2013 and April 2017 there have been 3,700 awards for Personal Independence Payment where the main disabling condition recorded was Crohn’s disease and 1,300 awards where the main disabling condition was ulcerative colitis.</p><p> </p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-09-06T10:17:47.557Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754241/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754241/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754241/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-07-19","Personal Independence Payment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people have received personal independence payments whose main disabling condition was recorded as Crohn's disease or ulcerative colitis since 2013.","false","Biography information for Mrs Anne Main","St Albans","Mrs Anne Main","6070"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754243","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-06","<p>The information requested is not available</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-09-06T10:18:56.76Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754243/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754243/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754243/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-07-19","Access to Work Programme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people have (a) applied for and (b) received support from the access to work scheme, whose main disabling condition was recorded as Crohn's disease, ulcerative colitis or inflammatory bowel disease, in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Mrs Anne Main","St Albans","Mrs Anne Main","6072"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754245","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-06","<p>Most DWP services are available in Welsh without the need for a request, via the online services provided by the Department through <a href="https://www.gov.uk/cymraeg" target="_blank">GOV.UK </a>:</p><p> </p><p>Jobseekers Allowance Online</p><p>Carer’s Allowance</p><p>Access to Work</p><p>Reporting Benefit Fraud</p><p>Universal Jobmatch</p><p>Budgeting Loan</p><p>Find a Lost Pension</p><p>Check Your State Pension</p><p>State Pension Online</p><p>Tell Us Once</p><p> </p><p>An Online complaints portal, to allow customers to raise any complaints about Jobseekers Allowance or Universal Credit, is also available in Welsh from the DWP corporate pages on <a href="https://www.gov.uk/" target="_blank">GOV.UK</a>.</p><p> </p><p>Universal Credit can be claimed online in English. We are planning a Welsh Language solution due in 2018. In the interim, Universal Credit can be claimed in Welsh over the telephone via our Service Centres.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-09-06T10:11:08.833Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754245/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754245/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754245/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-07-19","Department for Work and Pensions: Welsh Language","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, which of his Department's online services are available in the Welsh language only on request.","false","Biography information for Hywel Williams","Arfon","Hywel Williams","6064"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754246","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-06","<p>Government departments have been analysing the UK statute book and directly applicable EU law in their areas of responsibility to enable an assessment of the scale of the changes needed. This is likely to include the repeal, but also the amendment, of provisions in Acts but we are not in a position to give a sense of scale at this time.</p><p> </p><p>In the Government White Paper on the Repeal Bill ‘Legislating for the United Kingdom’s withdrawal from the European Union’, published on 30 March 2017, we estimated around 800 - 1,000 EU-exit related <strong>Statutory Instruments</strong> will be required.</p><p> </p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-09-06T10:09:47.713Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754246/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754246/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754246/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-07-19","Department for Work and Pensions: European Union (Withdrawal) Bill","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what estimate his Department has made of the potential number of Acts or parts of Acts that will be subject to repeal as a result of provisions in the European Union (Withdrawal) Bill.","false","Biography information for Hywel Williams","Arfon","Hywel Williams","6060"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754247","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-05","<p>We are committed to ensuring that older people receive the support they are entitled to and the Department targets activity on engaging with people who may be eligible at pivotal stages such as when they claim State Pension or report a change in their circumstances.</p><p> </p><p>We use a wide range of channels to communicate information about Pension Credit to potential customers; including information on gov.uk, in leaflets and by telephone.</p><p> </p><p>We believe that one of the best ways to reach those eligible customers who may be reluctant to claim is through trusted messengers working in the community and DWP provides a web-based Pension Credit toolkit at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/pension-credit-toolkit" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/pension-credit-toolkit</a> containing a range of resources for anyone working with pensioners. It contains guides to Pension Credit, examples of the reasons why eligible customers might not claim, ideas for encouraging take-up, and makes available a range of publicity material.</p>","Hexham","Guy Opperman",,"2017-09-05T11:02:56.373Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754247/answer","Biography information for Guy Opperman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754247/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754247/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-07-19","Pension Credit: Eligibility","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what steps his Department is taking to ensure that all those people eligible for pension credit are aware of their eligibility.","false","Biography information for Alex Cunningham","Stockton North","Alex Cunningham","6056"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754248","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-05","<p>Investigations into complaints about health assessors which have been made to professional bodies are the sole responsibility of the General Medical Council, Nursing and Midwifery Council and the Heath Care Professions Council.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-09-05T11:01:08.3Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754248/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754248/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754248/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-07-19","Social Security Benefits: Medical Examinations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many complaints about health assessors were investigated by each accredited professional body in each year since 2010-11 in relation to (a) work capability and (b) personal independence payment health assessments.","false","Biography information for Debbie Abrahams","Oldham East and Saddleworth","Debbie Abrahams","6035"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754249","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-05","<p>The Government intends to publish a White Paper on Defined Benefit pensions this coming winter.</p>","Hexham","Guy Opperman",,"2017-09-05T10:53:41.983Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754249/answer","Biography information for Guy Opperman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754249/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754249/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-07-19","Occupational Pensions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, when the Government plans to publish its White Paper on defined benefit pensions.","false","Biography information for Alex Cunningham","Stockton North","Alex Cunningham","6018"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754250","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-06","<p>The 20m distance is not the only factor considered when applying a descriptor for the Moving around activity. Individuals who can walk more than 20 metres can still receive the enhanced rate of the mobility component, if they cannot do so safely, to an acceptable standard, repeatedly and in a reasonable time period.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-09-06T10:41:37.327Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754250/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754250/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754250/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-07-19","Personal Independence Payment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will make it his policy to replace the 20 metre walking distance for personal independence payment mobility criterion with the 50 metre walking distance used for disability living allowance; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","6014"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754251","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-07","<p>The criteria for enhanced annuities on the grounds of ill health are set by individual pension providers in the terms and conditions of individual policies. Consumers should check with pension providers whether they are eligible for an enhanced annuity. As the Financial Conduct Authority’s recently published Retirement Outcomes Review interim report noted, over 90% of all enhanced annuities are purchased on the open market and consumers should shop around for the best possible deal.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay","6253","2017-09-07T15:50:15.247Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754251/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754251/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754251/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-07-19","Annuities","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what plans he has to make changes to the criteria for enhanced annuity on the grounds of ill health.","false","Biography information for Sir Gary Streeter","South West Devon","Mr Gary Streeter","6015"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754252","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-05","<p>The review was published on Wednesday 19 July 2017. Please find the below web link to the published report.</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/630065/state-pension-age-review-final-report.pdf" target="_blank">Governments State pension age review final report</a></p>","Hexham","Guy Opperman",,"2017-09-05T10:56:28.793Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754252/answer","Biography information for Guy Opperman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754252/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754252/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-07-19","State Pension Age Independent Review","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, when the Government plans to publish its response to the Cridland review.","false","Biography information for Alex Cunningham","Stockton North","Alex Cunningham","6019"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754253","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-05","<p>Legislation currently requires pension schemes to provide annual information and illustrations to scheme members about their pension pots. We are considering how members should be informed of the costs and charges that effect their pension savings.</p><p> </p><p>As part of the review of automatic enrolment we are looking at where more effective engagement could drive greater personal ownership and enable people to understand and maximise their savings. This review is due to report to Parliament at the end of the year.</p>","Hexham","Guy Opperman",,"2017-09-05T10:57:29.3Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754253/answer","Biography information for Guy Opperman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754253/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754253/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-07-19","Occupational Pensions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what steps he is taking to ensure that workers receive clear information about their pensions pots.","false","Biography information for Alex Cunningham","Stockton North","Alex Cunningham","6020"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754254","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-05","<p>By 2018, around 10 million people will be saving or saving more into pensions as a result of automatic enrolment. The Government wants to ensure that people who are automatically enrolled are protected from high and unfair charges. This is why in April 2015 we introduced a cap of 0.75% on administration charges for people who are invested in the default fund of schemes used for automatic enrolment. We have also taken steps to cap or ban early exit charges in occupational pension schemes, as these can act as a barrier to individuals wishing to access the pension freedoms. We have also banned member-borne commission charges in workplace pension schemes used for automatic enrolment.</p><p> </p><p>We are currently examining the level of the charge cap to see whether it should change and whether some or all the costs associated with investment transactions should also be covered. The Government expects to conclude its examination by the end of this year.</p><p> </p><p>In 2016, the Department for Work and Pensions and the Financial Conduct Authority (FCA) undertook a joint review on industry progress in reducing charge levels in older, so-called legacy pension schemes. The report published in December 2016 found that over 1 million customers have benefitted, or will soon benefit, from a reduction in costs and charges to 1% or lower. The Government and FCA wrote to these pension providers earlier this year challenging them to make further improvements. The Government is pleased with the progress so far and we and the FCA will continue to work with providers to ensure, wherever possible, that all members of these legacy schemes benefit from reduced charges.</p>","Hexham","Guy Opperman",,"2017-09-05T10:58:49.013Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754254/answer","Biography information for Guy Opperman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754254/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754254/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-07-19","Occupational Pensions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what steps he is taking to reduce explicit and implicit costs for workers saving into pensions.","false","Biography information for Alex Cunningham","Stockton North","Alex Cunningham","6021"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754255","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-06","<p>EU Exit is an all-of-government operation. The Department for Work and Pensions is working closely with the Department for Exiting the European Union to support the UK’s exit from the EU.</p><p> </p><p>Given the interactions between EU Exit work and the Department’s other priorities, it would not be possible to provide a precise figure on the annual expenditure of work relating to the UK leaving the EU.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-09-06T10:48:22.257Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754255/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754255/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754255/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-07-19","Department for Work and Pensions: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what amount of his Department's annual expenditure is allocated to work relating to the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Hywel Williams","Arfon","Hywel Williams","6022"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754256","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-06","<p>HM Government have not made an assessment of the effect of low pay on levels of social security spending.</p><p> </p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-09-06T10:08:01.487Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754256/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754256/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754256/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-07-19","Low Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment his Department has made of the effect of low pay on levels of social security spending for (a) public and (b) private sector employees by (i) industrial sector and (ii) region.","false","Biography information for Debbie Abrahams","Oldham East and Saddleworth","Debbie Abrahams","6004"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754257","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-06","<p>The Department is undertaking a review of the policy and operation of automatic enrolment, supported by an external Advisory Group. I refer you to the scope of this review set out by my Hon Friend Richard Harrington MP on 12 Dec 2016. It will look at the diverse group of self-employed people and how they might be better enabled to save for their retirement. The review report will be laid before Parliament at the end of the year.</p>","Hexham","Guy Opperman",,"2017-09-06T10:16:01.01Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754257/answer","Biography information for Guy Opperman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754257/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754257/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-07-19","Occupational Pensions: Self-employed","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what plans he has to bring self-employed workers into auto enrollment.","false","Biography information for Alex Cunningham","Stockton North","Alex Cunningham","6007"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754258","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-06","<p>It is important that pension savers know the costs and charges they are paying and the government is committed to making this happen. We want pension scheme members to have confidence that there are no hidden charges or fees being taken from their pots.</p><p> </p><p>Since 2015, we have required occupational and personal workplace pension schemes offering money purchase benefits, including master trust schemes, to produce an annual statement, which is available to members; which sets out the level of charges and, as far as they are able, transaction costs applicable to all funds; and the extent to which these charges and costs represent good value for members.</p><p> </p><p>It has previously been difficult for schemes to obtain information about the charges and transaction costs they incur. The Financial Conduct Authority (FCA) consulted last year on proposals requiring asset managers to disclose this information to trustees of occupational schemes offering money purchase benefits, and the governance committees for workplace personal pensions.</p><p> </p><p>The FCA will publish a Policy Statement later in the year setting out the final rules and guidance to disclose costs in a standardised format. We then intend to consult on how we can provide information about these costs and charges to the members of occupational schemes and to publish it. The FCA will, thereafter, introduce similar provisions for personal workplace pension schemes members.</p><p> </p><p>The FCA’s Asset Management Market Study indicated that there are significant issues with the way the investment market works. Savers, trustees, and scheme sponsors need a transparent, competitive and cost-effective investment market to provide for their security in later life and to keep their pension provision affordable. We will be studying the recommendations and proposed remedies closely to see what else government can do to support the FCA’s vital work in this area, which could deliver favourable outcomes for pension savers.</p><p> </p><p>To drive competitive pressure on asset managers the FCA recommended we look at barriers to scheme consolidation. We know that smaller pension schemes may not be able to negotiate or drive lower prices within this market, which in turn can lead to better outcomes for savers. Following a recent Call for Evidence, we are actively considering ways that we can simplify scheme consolidation and enable pension scheme scale to develop further.</p>","Hexham","Guy Opperman","6009 ; 6011 ; 6012 ; 6381 ; 6382","2017-09-06T10:27:04.493Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754258/answer","Biography information for Guy Opperman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754258/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754258/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-07-19","Occupational Pensions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what steps he is taking to secure a full transparent market for asset purchase and sales.","false","Biography information for Alex Cunningham","Stockton North","Alex Cunningham","6008"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754259","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-06","<p>It is important that pension savers know the costs and charges they are paying and the government is committed to making this happen. We want pension scheme members to have confidence that there are no hidden charges or fees being taken from their pots.</p><p> </p><p>Since 2015, we have required occupational and personal workplace pension schemes offering money purchase benefits, including master trust schemes, to produce an annual statement, which is available to members; which sets out the level of charges and, as far as they are able, transaction costs applicable to all funds; and the extent to which these charges and costs represent good value for members.</p><p> </p><p>It has previously been difficult for schemes to obtain information about the charges and transaction costs they incur. The Financial Conduct Authority (FCA) consulted last year on proposals requiring asset managers to disclose this information to trustees of occupational schemes offering money purchase benefits, and the governance committees for workplace personal pensions.</p><p> </p><p>The FCA will publish a Policy Statement later in the year setting out the final rules and guidance to disclose costs in a standardised format. We then intend to consult on how we can provide information about these costs and charges to the members of occupational schemes and to publish it. The FCA will, thereafter, introduce similar provisions for personal workplace pension schemes members.</p><p> </p><p>The FCA’s Asset Management Market Study indicated that there are significant issues with the way the investment market works. Savers, trustees, and scheme sponsors need a transparent, competitive and cost-effective investment market to provide for their security in later life and to keep their pension provision affordable. We will be studying the recommendations and proposed remedies closely to see what else government can do to support the FCA’s vital work in this area, which could deliver favourable outcomes for pension savers.</p><p> </p><p>To drive competitive pressure on asset managers the FCA recommended we look at barriers to scheme consolidation. We know that smaller pension schemes may not be able to negotiate or drive lower prices within this market, which in turn can lead to better outcomes for savers. Following a recent Call for Evidence, we are actively considering ways that we can simplify scheme consolidation and enable pension scheme scale to develop further.</p>","Hexham","Guy Opperman","6008 ; 6011 ; 6012 ; 6381 ; 6382","2017-09-06T10:27:04.557Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754259/answer","Biography information for Guy Opperman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754259/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754259/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-07-19","Investment: Fees and Charges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether he has identified the cost collection templates negotiated with the Investment Association as his Department's preferred methodology for cost collection.","false","Biography information for Alex Cunningham","Stockton North","Alex Cunningham","6009"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754260","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-06","<p>Although international comparisons are insightful it is difficult to draw a direct parallel due to different historical impacts and systems.</p><p> </p><p>The Government has and is continuing to work hard to ensure financial security in later life.</p><p>The UK system is based on a foundation income from the State in the form of the new State Pension, with provision above that from private saving, facilitated by auto-enrolment and pensions flexibilities. Thanks to triple lock, in April 2017, the basic state pension was over £1200 a year higher than it was in April 2010. The government is committed to the triple lock for the remainder of this parliament. The basic state pension it is now at one of its highest rates relative to earnings for over two decades, reversing a trend of decline we saw between 1997 and 2010.</p><p> </p><p>Recent reforms to private pensions including the introduction of Automatic Enrolment are also helping to improve retirement outcomes for future generations.</p>","Hexham","Guy Opperman",,"2017-09-06T10:37:10.847Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754260/answer","Biography information for Guy Opperman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754260/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754260/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-07-19","Pensions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, with reference to the Melbourne Mercer Global Pension Index, for what reasons pensioners in countries such as the Netherlands receive a 50 per cent higher income in retirement than their British counterparts.","false","Biography information for Alex Cunningham","Stockton North","Alex Cunningham","6010"
